"Nardone A., Ronchi B., Lacetera N., Ranieri M.S., Bernabucci U.","Effects of climate changes on animal production and sustainability of livestock systems",2010,"Livestock Science","130","1-3",,"57","69",,,10.1016/j.livsci.2010.02.011,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77951092978&partnerID=40&md5=537c7ef38b473544685ae84c241498a7","Dipartimento di Produzioni Animali, Università della Tuscia, via De Lellis, s.n.c. 01100 Viterbo, Italy","Nardone, A., Dipartimento di Produzioni Animali, Università della Tuscia, via De Lellis, s.n.c. 01100 Viterbo, Italy; Ronchi, B., Dipartimento di Produzioni Animali, Università della Tuscia, via De Lellis, s.n.c. 01100 Viterbo, Italy; Lacetera, N., Dipartimento di Produzioni Animali, Università della Tuscia, via De Lellis, s.n.c. 01100 Viterbo, Italy; Ranieri, M.S., Dipartimento di Produzioni Animali, Università della Tuscia, via De Lellis, s.n.c. 01100 Viterbo, Italy; Bernabucci, U., Dipartimento di Produzioni Animali, Università della Tuscia, via De Lellis, s.n.c. 01100 Viterbo, Italy","The effects of climate change are controversial. This paper reviews the effects of climate change on livestock following the theory of global warming. Although, the effects of global warming will not be adverse everywhere, a relevant increase of drought is expected across the world affecting forage and crop production. Hot environment impairs production (growth, meat and milk yield and quality, egg yield, weight, and quality) and reproductive performance, metabolic and health status, and immune response. The process of desertification will reduce the carrying capacity of rangelands and the buffering ability of agro-pastoral and pastoral systems. Other systems, such as mixed systems and industrial or landless livestock systems, could encounter several risk factors mainly due to the variability of grain availability and cost, and low adaptability of animal genotypes. Regarding livestock systems, it will be strategic to optimise productivity of crops and forage (mainly improving water and soil management), and to improve the ability of animals to cope with environmental stress by management and selection. To guide the evolution of livestock production systems under the increase of temperature and extreme events, better information is needed regarding biophysical and social vulnerability, and this must be integrated with agriculture and livestock components. © 2010 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Animal production; Climate change; Livestock production systems; Sustainability","Animalia",,,,,,"AIACC (Assessment of Impacts and Adaptation to Climate Change), (2006) Climate change and variability in the mixed crop/livestock production systems of the Argentinean, Brazilian and Uruguayan Pampas, , International START Secretariat, Washington, USA; Al-Katanani, Y.M., Webb, D.W., Hansen, P.J., Factors affecting seasonal variation in 90-day nonreturn rate to first service in lactating Holstein cows in a hot climate (1999) J. Dairy Sci., 82, pp. 2611-2616; Amundson, J.L., Mader, T.L., Rasby, R.J., Hu, Q.S., Environmental effects on pregnancy rate in beef cattle (2006) J. Anim. Sci., 84, pp. 3415-3420; Barati, F., Agung, B., Wongsrikeao, P., Taniguchi, M., Nagai, T., Otoi, T., Meiotic competence and DNA damage of porcine oocytes exposed to an elevated temperature (2008) Theriogenology, 69, pp. 767-772; Baumgard, L.H., Wheelock, J.B., O'Brien, M., Shwartz, G., Zimbelman, R.B., Sanders, S.R., VanBaale, M.J., Rhoads, R.P., The differential effects of heat stress vs. underfeeding on production and post-absorptive nutrient partitioning (2007) Proc. of the Southwest Nutrition and Management Conference, The University of Arizona, Tucson, February 23rd; Beard, C.W., Mitchell, B.W., Influence of environmental temperatures on the serologic responses of broiler chickens to inactivated and viable Newcastle disease vaccines (1987) Avian Dis., 31, pp. 321-326; Beede, D.K., Collier, R.J., Potential nutritional strategie